<h2 data-start="42" data-end="73">The Fall of the Roman Empire</h2>
<p data-start="75" data-end="284">The decline of the <strong data-start="94" data-end="135"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">Roman Empire</span></span></strong> was a prolonged process rather than a single event. It unfolded over several centuries and differed markedly between the western and eastern halves.</p>
<hr data-start="286" data-end="289">
<h3 data-start="291" data-end="318">Chronology (High Level)</h3>
<ul data-start="320" data-end="695">
<li data-start="320" data-end="415">
<p data-start="322" data-end="415"><strong data-start="322" data-end="340">3rd century CE</strong>: Systemic crisis—economic instability, civil wars, and external pressures.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="416" data-end="479">
<p data-start="418" data-end="479"><strong data-start="418" data-end="444">Late 4th–5th centuries</strong>: Accelerated collapse in the West.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="480" data-end="610">
<p data-start="482" data-end="610"><strong data-start="482" data-end="492">476 CE</strong>: Deposition of <strong data-start="508" data-end="549"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">Romulus Augustulus</span></span></strong>, conventionally marking the end of the Western Roman Empire.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="611" data-end="695">
<p data-start="613" data-end="695"><strong data-start="613" data-end="637">Eastern continuation</strong>: The Eastern Roman Empire (Byzantium) endured until 1453.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="697" data-end="700">
<h3 data-start="702" data-end="720">Primary Causes</h3>
<h4 data-start="722" data-end="751">1. Political Instability</h4>
<ul data-start="752" data-end="895">
<li data-start="752" data-end="825">
<p data-start="754" data-end="825">Frequent civil wars and rapid turnover of emperors weakened governance.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="826" data-end="895">
<p data-start="828" data-end="895">Power struggles diverted resources from defense and administration.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h4 data-start="897" data-end="921">2. Economic Decline</h4>
<ul data-start="922" data-end="1105">
<li data-start="922" data-end="993">
<p data-start="924" data-end="993">Heavy taxation, currency debasement, and inflation eroded confidence.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="994" data-end="1056">
<p data-start="996" data-end="1056">Reliance on slave labor reduced innovation and productivity.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1057" data-end="1105">
<p data-start="1059" data-end="1105">Long supply lines strained imperial logistics.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h4 data-start="1107" data-end="1133">3. Military Pressures</h4>
<ul data-start="1134" data-end="1322">
<li data-start="1134" data-end="1196">
<p data-start="1136" data-end="1196">Increasing dependence on mercenaries with divided loyalties.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1197" data-end="1261">
<p data-start="1199" data-end="1261">Major defeats (e.g., Adrianople, 378) exposed vulnerabilities.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1262" data-end="1322">
<p data-start="1264" data-end="1322">Invasions by Goths, Vandals, Huns, and others intensified.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h4 data-start="1324" data-end="1360">4. Administrative Overextension</h4>
<ul data-start="1361" data-end="1564">
<li data-start="1361" data-end="1436">
<p data-start="1363" data-end="1436">The empire’s size outpaced its capacity to govern and defend effectively.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1437" data-end="1564">
<p data-start="1439" data-end="1564">Reforms by <strong data-start="1450" data-end="1491"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">Diocletian</span></span></strong> (e.g., tetrarchy) improved short-term stability but entrenched division.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<h4 data-start="1566" data-end="1600">5. Cultural and Social Shifts</h4>
<ul data-start="1601" data-end="1764">
<li data-start="1601" data-end="1671">
<p data-start="1603" data-end="1671">Gradual transformation of civic identity and military service norms.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1672" data-end="1764">
<p data-start="1674" data-end="1764">Christianity’s rise altered state priorities and institutions (often debated as a factor).</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="1766" data-end="1769">
<h3 data-start="1771" data-end="1788">East vs. West</h3>
<ul data-start="1790" data-end="2084">
<li data-start="1790" data-end="1916">
<p data-start="1792" data-end="1916"><strong data-start="1792" data-end="1816">Western Roman Empire</strong>: Weaker economy, fewer urban centers, heavier frontier pressure; collapsed by the late 5th century.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="1917" data-end="2084">
<p data-start="1919" data-end="2084"><strong data-start="1919" data-end="1943">Eastern Roman Empire</strong>: Wealthier, more urbanized, strategically positioned; stabilized under <strong data-start="2015" data-end="2056"><span class="hover:entity-accent entity-underline inline cursor-pointer align-baseline"><span class="whitespace-normal">Constantine the Great</span></span></strong> and persisted as Byzantium.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="2086" data-end="2089">
<h3 data-start="2091" data-end="2115">Aftermath and Legacy</h3>
<ul data-start="2117" data-end="2345">
<li data-start="2117" data-end="2169">
<p data-start="2119" data-end="2169">Western Europe fragmented into successor kingdoms.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2170" data-end="2249">
<p data-start="2172" data-end="2249">Roman law, infrastructure, and culture continued to shape medieval societies.</p>
</li>
<li data-start="2250" data-end="2345">
<p data-start="2252" data-end="2345">The Eastern Empire preserved classical knowledge, influencing later Renaissance transmission.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<hr data-start="2347" data-end="2350">
<h3 data-start="2352" data-end="2368">Key Takeaway</h3>
<p data-start="2370" data-end="2604">The fall of Rome was <strong data-start="2391" data-end="2421">gradual and multifactorial</strong>—a convergence of political, economic, military, and administrative stresses—ending Western imperial rule in 476 CE while the East adapted and survived for nearly a millennium longer.</p>
